<br>
--- <br>
<br>
Shaede paced slowly, lost in her own thoughts as the flogging continued. The crack of the whip barely registered in her mind any more, for it had been going on for such a long time. Restlessly she sat in the chair by the door, and pulled out one of the tomes from her pack. She regretted not taking the Reaper’s advice. She simply could not focus on the text while she watched him hang there in chains, still as death.<br>
<br>
She tried to concentrate, turning to a marked page to reread a particularly troublesome section. It was hard going, but finally she was able to lose herself in the work of translation.<br>
<br>
Suddenly Khasirath let out a choking cry of agony, and Shaede almost dropped her book. She stood and tossed the tome onto the chair as she rushed to the Reaper. As she came around in front of him she gasped. His face was covered in blood that streamed from deep ugly gouges around his eyes. His eyes were still shut tightly, his face twisted in pain.<br>
<br>
Shaede drew an enchantment into herself, the mana of the spell sparkling faintly as it settled into her eyes, allowing her to see invisible things. Quickly she looked around the room, but there was nothing there but the Reaper, the Prophetess, her elemental and herself.<br>
<br>
Shaede gently touched Khasirath’s face, her hand trembling. His skin was still burning hot, and he did not react at all. His breathing was rapid now, but still frighteningly shallow.<br>
<br>
Shaede turned to Vhalshae, and noticed the girl’s face was ashen as she continued her chanting and whipping. “What is happening? What did this to him?”<br>
<br>
The Prophetess swallowed hard, almost stuttering as she tried to answer, “It is the Father’s Will, Shaede…” Her voice was soft and distant.<br>
<br>
Shaede shook her head slowly, looking at the Reaper’s face. His pain was so apparent, though he was still once more. She watched him for a long moment, not knowing what to do, too confused even to know what to think.<br>
<br>
Khasirath groaned in pain, his body stiffening in the chains. Shaede bit her lip as she watched him writhe. His eyelids fluttered open weakly, and a wash of blood and clear vitreous poured down his cheeks. Shaede clasped a hand to her mouth to choke back a cry as she saw his empty eye sockets before his eyes closed again, and he fell back into unconsciousness.<br>
<br>
“My god… What can we do?” Shaede asked the Prophetess.<br>
<br>
Vhalshae shook her head, almost trembling as she continued to work the whip. “Pray, Shaede. Pray for him.”<br>
<br>
--- <br>
<br>
Innoruuk’s talons were like lances of white-hot flame as they clawed at Khasirath’s face. He pierced the Knight’s eyes, His claws twisting skillfully in the sockets like a vendor working flavored ice, removing every last trace of his violet orbs. Frozen in place, Khasirath could not even scream as the agony seared his soul. The God’s hateful laughter filled the cathedral and Khasirath’s mind, mingling with the endless torment.<br>
<br>
Innoruuk withdrew His talons, but the pain raged on, and Khasirath feared it might very well destroy him. He heard and felt the God drawing closer yet, bending down as His dark aura crashed into the Knight’s soul, smothering him in its Hatred.<br>
<br>
He felt the breath of the God wash over his face, the acrid blood scent enveloping him as the breath filled his empty eye sockets. It burned within his head, the acid mist swirling and eddying within his sockets, solidifying slowly. Within his soul he screamed, desperate to give release to the suffering. Never had he felt pain like this, not even under the Father’s Touch.<br>
<br>
Like a puppeteer cutting the strings, Innoruuk released the paralysis, and Khasirath crumpled to the floor of the chancel. The Reaper writhed and spasmed, trying to scream, but all that could escape his seizing lungs was a whimpering groan. For a long time he thrashed, but eventually his strength was spent and he lay still, trembling hard under the endless pain.<br>
<br>
Innoruuk sat back on His Throne, and Khasirath could feel the perverse satisfaction rolling in waves from the God.<br>
<br>
“I am pleased with you, my child.” Innoruuk said, the dark chuckle still ringing in his words.<br>
<br>
“But you are blind as a newborn. You refuse to see what in under your very nose, so you come fumbling for a teat from which to draw what you need.”<br>
<br>
Khasirath heard the Father’s talons clawing at the arm of His Throne. The keening sound made him tremble even harder as he absorbed the Father’s words.<br>
<br>
“The truth is all around you, child. When your eyes open, perhaps you will be more inclined to perceive,” Innoruuk growled.<br>
<br>
With that, Khasirath was suddenly falling. He panicked, flailing. He could see nothing at all; only feel the wind rushing past, and the sickening twisting in his gut as he plummeted. The smell of blood surrounded him.<br>
<br>
And as he fell, suddenly he could see… a hundred pairs of lupine eyes glaring at him with cold and limitless hunger. The eyes seemed to float upon a misty sea of blood, and they were all the same shifting green-jade color. The vision sustained itself for a few heartbeats, then the eyes faded away into the sea of blood, and the sea itself faded to black, leaving Khasirath sightless once more.<br>
<br>
With a sickening jerk, Khasirath found himself back in his physical body, strung from the cold chains, and lost to the crushing pain.<br>
<br>
--- <br>
<br>
Khasirath let out a deep groan full of pain and loss. Shaede jumped at the sudden sound, biting her lip as she saw the way he trembled and writhed. His head lolled from side to side as he continued to moan.<br>
<br>
Vhalshae tossed the whip back onto the chest. “Get him down, quickly.”<br>
<br>
Shaede hurried to open the manacles, though the clasps were tight from Khasirath’s weight. As he came free she couldn’t hold him up, only control his fall to the floor. His wrists were deeply gouged from the metal manacles, his back covered in blood.<br>
<br>
Vhalshae brought over a box of bandages and salves, and began to tend to the Reaper’s wounds. Shaede grabbed up some of the supplies to help. Khasirath was senseless from the pain, shivering hard as he weakly moaned through the bandaging.<br>
<br>
Vhalshae gently opened his eyes as she tended to the scratches surrounding them. Shaede caught sight of it as she worked, and was shocked to see that swirling white pupil-less orbs filled his eye sockets. A shudder went through her as she watched Vhalshae finish applying salve to the scratches and wrap gauze around Khasirath’s face, covering his eyes completely.<br>
<br>
Once the bandaging was complete, Vhalshae lifted Khas’s head onto her lap, rousing him enough to help him drink another tea she had prepared. After he drank he calmed somewhat.<br>
<br>
“Khasirath… will you be alright?” Shaede asked.<br>
<br>
His voice was weak and pained, “Aye, Shaede. The Father found me worthy enough to return to Norrath.”<br>
<br>
“But your eyes…” she whispered.<br>
<br>
Khasirath sighed deeply, “I do not think He will make me remain this way. He implied my sight would be restored. A Knight without sight would be worthless to the Father.”<br>
<br>
As she watched him lay there, Shaede could see it was only his faith that kept the Reaper from falling into panic.<br>
